Travelpoints.

A travelpoint sends the player to a different map. Standing inside its trigger area and pressing the interact key loads a named destination map and drops the player at a chosen position in it, with a line of spoken text announcing the arrival. Travelpoints are how a world is stitched together out of separate maps — a doorway from the town map into a shop map, a cave mouth that leads to the cavern map, a staircase that continues onto the next floor's map.

A travelpoint is the cross-map transition. To move the player within the current map, use a teleporter; to move them between heights, use a lift or an elevator. The travelpoint is the only one of these that changes which map the player is on.

How a travelpoint works.

A travelpoint is a trigger area, built in two variants chosen from the build mode list: single (one tile) and ranged (a rectangular area). When the player is anywhere inside that area and presses the interact key, the named destination map loads, the player is placed at the destination coordinates within it, and the destination text is spoken so the player knows where they've arrived. If the destination map exists, a transition sound plays as the new map comes up.

Because a travelpoint loads a whole map, the destination coordinates are a position in that other map, not the current one — so you set them to wherever the player should appear once they're there, such as just inside the shop's entrance or at the foot of the cavern's first corridor.

Travelpoint fields.

The travelpoint form takes the following:

Coordinates. A single travelpoint takes an x and y (and z on 3d maps) for its trigger tile. A ranged travelpoint takes minimum and maximum x and y instead (and min and max z on 3d maps) for the trigger rectangle, so the player can step across a wide threshold rather than one exact tile. The ranged form is selected from the build mode list.

Destination map. The name of the map to load when the travelpoint is used — the same name the map has in the builder.

Destination position. The destination x and y (and z on 3d maps) where the player will appear in the destination map.

Destination text. A line spoken to the player on arrival, for example you step into the marketplace or the air turns cold as you enter the cave. Use it to set the scene or simply to confirm the move.

A travelpoint has no sound theme to choose — it uses a built-in transition sound when it sends the player off, so there's no sound list in its form.

Authoring travelpoints by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a single travelpoint is: travelpoint x y "destination map" "destination text" destx desty. On 3d maps a z is inserted after the trigger y and a destination z after the destination y: travelpoint x y z "destination map" "destination text" destx desty destz.

The ranged form replaces the single trigger tile with minimum and maximum pairs: travelpoint minx maxx miny maxy "destination map" "destination text" destx desty, inserting min and max z after the y pair and a destination z after the destination y on 3d maps. Both forms share the one travelpoint name; the game reads the line as ranged when there are more coordinate values before the quoted destination map than a single travelpoint would have.

The destination map name and the destination text are each wrapped in double quotes so they may contain spaces. The destination position is plain numbers.
